{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1d2f6b5e-ccb5-4bb6-aef6-6a052c62b72f","content":"The template is **structurally valid** but **not ready to publish** as-is. Here are the issues:\n\n**Must fix:**\n- **Placeholder values** — `identity`, `author`, and `sourceName` all use generic \"MyCompany\" / \"My Company\" names. Replace with your actual org/package identity.\n- **Missing `$schema`** — add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation and IDE support.\n- **Missing `description`** — critical for NuGet discoverability. Users won't know what your template does.\n\n**Recommended:**\n- **No `groupIdentity`** — helps group related templates (e.g., `MyCompany.WebApi`).\n- **No `preferNameDirectory`** — should be `true` for project templates.\n- **No `defaultName`** — controls the fallback project name when the user doesn't specify one.\n\n**Note:** This file alone doesn't get published — you'll also need a `.csproj` or `.nuspec` with `<PackageType>Template</PackageType>` and proper NuGet metadata (version, license, etc.) to produce a publishable package.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"76a53dfb-0e25-41a1-b7f2-99b84c0fb565","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. Let me check the required and recommended fields for a .NET template.\n\nKey things to check:\n1. `$schema` - missing, recommended for validation\n2. `identity` - present ✓\n3. `name` - present ✓\n4. `shortName` - present ✓\n5. `author` - present ✓ (but generic placeholder)\n6. `classifications` - present ✓\n7. `tags` - present with language and type ✓\n8. `sourceName` - present ✓\n\n\n9. `symbols` - present ✓\n10. `groupIdentity` - missing, recommended for grouping related templates\n11. `precedence` - missing (useful when multiple versions exist)\n12. `preferNameDirectory` - missing (common for project templates)\n13. `defaultName` - missing (what the project is named if user doesn't specify)\n\nThe templa